      Crypto bank runs
   =20
 =20

One possibility is that=20
fractional reserve banking is deeply rooted in human nature. People have mo=
ney, they would like to keep it somewhere safe, they would like it to grow,=
 they would like to be able to get it back at any time. Other people need m=
oney, they are willing to pay to borrow it, but they want it for a long tim=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0they want to be able to use it to buy a house or build a b=
usiness; they don=E2=80=99t want their lender to be able to demand the mone=
y back at any time. The savers and the borrowers just want different things=
. Why would=C2=A0anyone want to lock their money up for a long time? Why=C2=
=A0would=C2=A0anyone want to borrow money for an uncertain time?
If you are an enterprising middleman, you can try to convince one side or t=
he other to do something that doesn=E2=80=99t quite match their desires =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cinvest your money long-term, but if you need it back w=
e can probably=C2=A0find a way to get it to you,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cborro=
w short-term, but you can probably=C2=A0keep rolling your debt for a long t=
ime=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but it is easier and more appealing to just promise =
everyone exactly what they want. People who want to park their money give i=
t to you and you promise to give it back whenever they want; people who wan=
t to borrow money borrow it from you and you tell them they=C2=A0can keep i=
t for a long time;=C2=A0probably=C2=A0this all works out, but the mismatch =
is now your problem, not theirs. Of course it is also their problem, since =
if it doesn=E2=80=99t work out you are probably bankrupt. But you don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0tell=C2=A0them that it=E2=80=99s their problem. This is better ma=
rketing.
This most obviously describes the=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmaturity transformation=E2=
=80=9D function of traditional banking, =E2=80=9Ca superposition of=C2=A0fr=
aud and genius that interposes itself between investors and entrepreneurs,=
=E2=80=9D in  Steve Randy Waldman=E2=80=99s words. But it also describes a =
whole range of shadow banking activities, some of which are more genius and=
 others of which are more fraud. We have talked about   Greensill Capital, =
which was in the business of using investor money to finance companies=E2=
=80=99 receivables: A company would sell a product to a buyer on credit and=
 Greensill would advance it the cash against the bill. Companies said =E2=
=80=9Cwell that=E2=80=99s fine but we=E2=80=99d rather get longer-term unse=
cured loans,=E2=80=9D and Greensill was like =E2=80=9Cah well we can call t=
hat a loan against=C2=A0future=C2=A0receivables,=E2=80=9D and it had a clas=
sic business of telling its investors that they were lending short-term, te=
lling its borrowers that they were borrowing long-term, and ending up in a =
lot of trouble.
Or there is crypto, which to some extent=C2=A0started=C2=A0as a backlash to=
 fractional reserve banking and the shadow banking crisis of 2008, and by l=
ast year had matured to the point that it recreated both fractional reserve=
=C2=A0banking (but without regulation!) and a 2008-style shadow banking cri=
sis. People in crypto did not trust the banks, in part for the good reason =
that the banks were doing something (maturity transformation) that is both =
risky and in some deep sense deceptive. But people in crypto did=C2=A0want=
=C2=A0the benefits of maturity transformation: People with crypto wanted to=
 park it somewhere safe, earn interest and have access to it whenever they =
wanted; other people wanted to borrow crypto without the risk of having to =
give it back early. Crypto shadow banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0Celsius,   Voyager, =
  BlockFi, Genesis,   Gemini Earn,   FTX =E2=80=94=C2=A0sprung up to offer =
that service, to borrow short and lend long. Free of most regulation, they =
could offer the service efficiently, market it aggressively, and lose tons =
of their customers=E2=80=99 money.
In some sense you know that crypto has made it because Gary Gorton wrote a =
paper about runs on crypto shadow banks. Here is =E2=80=9CBank Runs During =
Crypto Winter,=E2=80=9D by Gorton and Jeffery Zhang:

=E2=80=9CCrypto Winter=E2=80=9D refers to a systemic event that occurred in=
 the cryptocurrency ecosystem=E2=80=94what we call =E2=80=9Ccrypto space=E2=
=80=9D=E2=80=94in 2022. Crypto space was wracked by plummeting crypto price=
s, the troubles of a large crypto hedge fund, and runs on many crypto lendi=
ng platforms. Several large crypto firms went bankrupt, and households and =
firms lost billions of dollars. Crypto investors are still feeling the afte=
rshocks.
We begin with two observations. First, despite mass marketing campaigns to =
the contrary, crypto lending platforms recreated banking all over again. Cr=
ypto lending platforms were vulnerable to runs because, like all banks, the=
y borrowed short and lent long. This is the essence of banking, so we label=
 these lending platforms =E2=80=9Ccrypto banks.=E2=80=9D Second, crypto spa=
ce was largely circular. Once crypto banks obtained deposits and investment=
s, these firms borrowed, lent, and traded mostly with themselves. As a resu=
lt, Crypto Winter did not cause the kind of financial turmoil that we witne=
ssed in either 2008 or 2020, and it did not cause an economic recession.
We then pivot to a warning for regulators. The next generation of crypto fi=
rms are linking up with the financial sector, which means their failures wi=
ll spill over into the real economy. To contain the inevitable growth of sy=
stemic risk, regulators should use banking laws to address a banking proble=
m.

=E2=80=9CCrypto space was largely circular=E2=80=9D: Whereas traditional ba=
nking borrows short to lend long to people who want to build houses or star=
t businesses, crypto shadow banking borrows crypto short to lend crypto lon=
g to people who want to speculate on cryptocurrencies. In some sense you=E2=
=80=99d expect this to create less of a maturity mismatch =E2=80=94=C2=A0ho=
w long does anyone really need to borrow for to day-trade cryptocurrencies?=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but on the other hand the collateral is much riskier. If yo=
u borrow to buy a house and default, the bank gets the house. If you borrow=
 to buy some magic beans and default, the bank gets some beans.
One point that Gorton and Zhang make is that, in the US, efforts at crypto =
regulation are largely about either securities law or commodities regulatio=
n, but the actual problem of 2022 was=C2=A0banking.=C2=A0Securities regulat=
ion is about giving investors=C2=A0full information so they can make inform=
ed decisions about what companies to invest in. Bank regulation is the oppo=
site; it assumes that bank depositors should=C2=A0not=C2=A0have to care muc=
h about what their banks are up to; bankers and=C2=A0regulators and supervi=
sors worry about a bank=E2=80=99s asset quality and liquidity and capital r=
atios so that   depositors can be information-insensitive. To the extent cr=
ypto is re-creating=C2=A0banking, regulators should respond by re-creating=
=C2=A0bank regulation. And a cornerstone of modern bank regulation is depos=
it insurance. Gorton and Zhang write:
In all likelihood, applying banking law to crypto banks would require an ac=
t of Congress. Doing so would subject crypto banks to rigorous regulation b=
ut would also provide crypto banks with deposit insurance paired with enhan=
ced supervision.
I mean! That is one approach. My impression is that most people running cry=
pto exchanges=C2=A0really=C2=A0would not like US banking regulators to tell=
 them where to invest their money (=E2=80=9Cnot crypto=E2=80=9D?), and also=
 that most US regulators=C2=A0really=C2=A0would not like to guarantee the l=
iabilities of crypto exchanges? US regulators are   not all that sure that =
crypto exchanges are legal. If your concern is that crypto shadow banks are=
 becoming more interconnected with the real economy, and that therefore fut=
ure runs on those shadow banks might be more destructive, there are two way=
s to go:
=09Protect crypto shadow banks from runs, with deposit insurance and regula=
tion; or=09Protect the real economy from crypto shadow banks, by making it =
really hard for the traditional financial system to connect with crypto fir=
ms.

US regulators seem to be choosing Option 2, which =E2=80=A6 seems =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0right =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to me? As a matter of regulatory preferences but=
 also as a matter of crypto=E2=80=99s=C2=A0preferences. Just imagine implem=
enting Option 1. Imagine the meeting between the US Federal Deposit Insuran=
ce Corp. and, like, Tether, to talk about supervision and deposit insurance=
.=C2=A0
Meanwhile here is a Chicago Fed Letter by Radhika Patel and Jonathan Rose t=
itled=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA Retrospective on the Crypto Runs of 2022=E2=80=9D:
In this article, we describe the spectacular collapse of several crypto-ass=
et platforms in 2022 following investment losses and widespread customer wi=
thdrawals. These platforms offered and marketed to customers a number of pr=
oducts and services related to crypto-assets, including high-yield investme=
nts, trading, and custody services. The platforms were subject to run risk:=
 They allowed customers to withdraw funds on demand while using those funds=
 to make illiquid and risky investments, in part to generate the high rates=
 of returns promised to customers on investment products. In one of the mos=
t severe episodes, customers withdrew a quarter of their investments from t=
he platform FTX in just one day, according to our analysis of data from its=
 bankruptcy filing. These episodes together formed a classic financial cris=
is in a novel setting that has raised urgent policy concerns.
One finding here is that the crypto shadow banks had very=C2=A0fast=C2=A0ru=
ns; crypto shadow banking sort of necessarily takes place online, =E2=80=9C=
with customers withdrawing funds through apps or web portals with ease.=E2=
=80=9D When there were runs on US regional banks this spring, it seems that=
 bankers and regulators were surprised by the speed of the bank runs in an =
era of largely app- and web-based banking. I suppose the crypto bank runs f=
oreshadowed that a bit.
Another finding is that, =E2=80=9Cwhile the platforms had many retail clien=
ts, the runs were spearheaded by customers with large holdings, some of whi=
ch were sophisticated institutional customers.=E2=80=9D This is related to =
the circularity of crypto that Gorton and Zhang write about: Crypto shadow =
banks were borrowing from and lending to each other, crypto hedge funds wer=
e borrowing from one platform to lend on another platform, and so they were=
 particularly attuned to the risks of those platforms. In a sense crypto sh=
adow banks were trying to provide information-insensitive deposits, but in =
another sense nothing in crypto is really information-insensitive: Everyone=
=E2=80=99s account on every crypto platform is a gambling account; nobody h=
as their money at Celsius just because that=E2=80=99s where their employer =
direct deposited their paycheck and that=E2=80=99s where their automatic bi=
ll-pay is set up.
  [1]
=C2=A0Crypto depositors are just naturally going to be more risk-aware than=
 bank depositors, which makes crypto shadow banks more run-prone.
Another finding is that the crypto shadow banks were pretty bad banks:
Efforts to generate high returns caused these platforms to hold insufficien=
t liquidity buffers. At FTX, Bankman-Fried stated that FTX had held enough =
liquidity to meet 24 times average daily withdrawals, which he stated turne=
d out to be 80% of what was withdrawn in one day at the height of the run. =
Celsius used an internal stress scenario that assumed a 20% outflow of cust=
omer funds in response to 40%=E2=80=9350% price drops, which would appear t=
o be a conservative scenario; however, in 2022, when Celsius=E2=80=99s liqu=
idity buffer became insufficient according to that stress scenario, the com=
pany adopted a weaker scenario involving smaller price drops. BlockFi=E2=80=
=99s liquidity strategy aimed to hold 10% of customer funds in assets that =
can be immediately liquidated and 50% in assets that could be liquidated wi=
thin seven calendar days. All of these liquidity buffers were evidently ins=
ufficient, and it is hard to verify whether they ever existed.
What conclusion do you draw about bank regulation here? Like:
=09Crypto shadow banks had inadequate liquidity buffers, so they should hav=
e been regulated, because US banking regulators would have made them have h=
igher liquidity buffers; or=09Crypto shadow banks had inadequate=C2=A0liqui=
dity buffers, because their business of lending against volatile collateral=
 was incredibly risky and run-prone, and if US banking regulators had super=
vised these platforms they probably=C2=A0still=C2=A0would have had runs and=
 gone bust (like several actual banks did recently!), but it would be the g=
overnment=E2=80=99s fault?

Meanwhile at Bloomberg,  Emily Nicolle reports that many big crypto compani=
es do not have audited financial statements or independent =E2=80=94=C2=A0o=
r, often, any =E2=80=94=C2=A0boards of directors:

Bloomberg News surveyed 60 major crypto companies in the first quarter =E2=
=80=94 spanning the breadth of exchanges, mining companies, analytics busin=
esses and token issuers =E2=80=94 to gauge the state of governance and cont=
rols in the sector. 1 Many of these companies, which include the likes of B=
inance, Coinbase Global Inc., Tether and OpenSea, oversee the flow of tens =
of billions of dollars in assets daily. And while a fair number do adhere t=
o traditional standards, many operate outside the norm. =E2=80=A6
Around half of the businesses surveyed currently engage an independent audi=
tor to assess their finances, the findings showed. Meanwhile, 63% of the co=
mpanies had an independent board of directors =E2=80=93 meaning that they h=
ad at least one non-executive member. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Among those without in=
dependent boards were Tether, Huobi and Magic Eden, whose boards were eithe=
r only advisory or entirely staffed by company executives.

Also=C2=A0at Bloomberg, here is Christopher Beam with =E2=80=9CTales From t=
he Crypto Winter.=E2=80=9D Beam=E2=80=99s friend George is still a believer=
:

George, despite the frauds, the constant hacks and the market=E2=80=99s col=
lapse, says he still has faith. =E2=80=9CI still believe blockchain is a re=
volutionary development,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CIn 10, 20, 50 years, I =
do believe=E2=80=94I want to believe, badly=E2=80=94that we=E2=80=99ll look=
 back and say Bitcoin was an invention on the scale of the printing press o=
r the internet.=E2=80=9D
In their seminal 1956 social psychology study, When Prophecy Fails, Leon Fe=
stinger, Henry Riecken and Stanley Schachter described how followers of a d=
oomsday cult responded when their prophet=E2=80=99s precise predictions of =
apocalypse turned out to be false: They just pushed the date back. Some bec=
ame even stronger believers and proselytized more. They=E2=80=99d already c=
ommitted too much, perhaps quitting their jobs or giving away money, to acc=
ept that there was nothing to it. The study became a classic example of the=
 =E2=80=9Ccognitive dissonance=E2=80=9D that occurs when evidence contradic=
ts one=E2=80=99s model of the world.

Oh and here is =E2=80=9CBitcoin Bulls Trip on a Frog as  Pepe Memecoin Fren=
zy Signals Market Top=E2=80=9D:

A frog-themed digital token that=E2=80=99s only been around for a month may=
 be signaling pain ahead for Bitcoin bulls.
Trading in memecoins =E2=80=94 crypto assets that can be inspired by viral =
images and memes and attract loyal social-media communities but otherwise l=
ack in inherent utility =E2=80=94 soared in recent days. Leading the pack w=
as Pepe, a newfangled amphibian-themed token, which sparked frenzied specul=
ation and spawned many copycats ever since its birth in April.=C2=A0
Pepe was obsessively promoted on Twitter before and after its launch, and i=
t peaked at a market value of more than $1.6 billion on May 5 before revers=
ing course and plummeting as much as 70% in following days, according to Co=
inMarketCap. The ill-fated frog =E2=80=94 which, like many memecoins, never=
 traded higher than a fraction of a cent even at its height =E2=80=94 took =
Bitcoin and Ether down with it. Both coins have dropped about 10% since May=
 5, a notable step-down after four straight months of gains.

Yep yep yep the printing press, absolutely.

