      Tiger Global=C2=A0
   =20
 =20

In the startup boom of recent years, Tiger Global Management got a reputati=
on for investing in every startup, moving fast,=C2=A0paying top dollar and =
not being too involved in governance. This always  struck me as sort of a c=
lever differentiation. A  reasonable model of venture capital investing,=C2=
=A0particularly during a boom, is something like:
=09Most of the returns of venture investing come from a few big home-run de=
als, so the trick is to be in those.=09Due diligence and careful deal selec=
tion don=E2=80=99t matter very much: Being in the handful of big home runs =
and losing 100% on a bunch of other deals is better than missing some home =
runs and avoiding most of the losers.=09Valuation doesn=E2=80=99t matter ve=
ry much: Overpaying for the handful of big home runs is better than missing=
 them.=09What matters is=C2=A0getting into all of the good deals, which mea=
ns acquiring a reputation, with startup founders, for being easy to work wi=
th.=09=E2=80=9CEasy to work with=E2=80=9D certainly means moving fast and p=
aying top dollar.=09Some VCs clearly think that it also means something lik=
e =E2=80=9Cbringing my expertise and wisdom to the board of directors,=E2=
=80=9D but Tiger Global=C2=A0plausibly concluded that saying =E2=80=9Cnah, =
we don=E2=80=99t need a board seat, we trust you=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0calling startup founders to share their wisdom would actually be receive=
d pretty well.=09Also, by moving fast, paying top dollar and not doing much=
 diligence, Tiger Global got a lot of=C2=A0press=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0often =
quoting other VCs complaining about them =E2=80=94=C2=A0which probably insp=
ired some startup founders to say =E2=80=9Chey, actually these guys sound g=
ood, let=E2=80=99s call them.=E2=80=9D

Just a smart approach to a certain moment in the venture capital marketplac=
e. On the other hand that moment is over and now here=E2=80=99s this:

Technology-focused hedge fund Tiger Global is exploring options to cash in =
a piece of its more than $40bn portfolio of privately held companies, accor=
ding to people familiar with the matter.
The New York-based investment group is working with an adviser to tap the s=
o-called secondary market to help return money to some of its investors, th=
e people said.
Talks are at an early stage and potential buyers have said that any deal wo=
uld probably be complicated by difficulties valuing Tiger=E2=80=99s private=
 holdings, which include stakes in companies such as payments business Stri=
pe, US software group Databricks and China=E2=80=99s ByteDance, some of the=
 people said. =E2=80=A6
Over the past few years, investors in fast-growing companies such as Tiger =
have been able to realise gains by taking companies public. However, initia=
l public offerings have slowed over the past 18 months as investors grapple=
 with wider inflationary pressures and stock market volatility. =E2=80=A6
In 2022, Tiger=E2=80=99s flagship fund suffered its worst annual loss, losi=
ng more than 50 per cent of its value as Tiger marked down its unlisted hol=
dings by nearly 20 per cent. Some of its funds have recorded small gains fo=
r unlisted assets this year, however.

And here the reputation probably does not help? If you go to the secondary =
market with a bunch of startup stakes and a reputation for paying top dolla=
r and not doing much due diligence, people are going to want a discount.

