Both the  Wall Street Journal and  Insider have stories on the race to succ=
eed Larry Fink as chief executive officer of BlackRock Inc.; they have slig=
htly different shortlists of potential successors. Insider also has  an org=
 chart of =E2=80=9Cthe 150 most powerful people under CEO Larry Fink as suc=
cession planning looms,=E2=80=9D and one thing=C2=A0I enjoyed in the org ch=
art is that the guy who seems to be in charge of investing the money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the head of the portfolio management group=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0is =
two levels below Fink. Fink has 12 direct reports, and one of those direct =
reports (President Rob Kapito) has 10 direct reports, and one of=C2=A0those=
=C2=A0direct reports is Rich Kushel, the head of portfolio management. A na=
ive model of BlackRock is something like =E2=80=9CBlackRock controls a pool=
 of  $9 trillion and decides how to invest it,=E2=80=9D but it is sort of s=
triking how small a part of BlackRock=E2=80=99s business the deciding-where=
-to-invest-the-money part is. Raising the money, doing stewardship, buildin=
g technology, lots of other things also seem to occupy a lot of time.
Incidentally Kushel is on Insider=E2=80=99s, but not the Journal=E2=80=99s,=
 list of potential successors. Investing the money is not necessarily the m=
ain thing that BlackRock does, but I suppose it is good preparation for run=
ning BlackRock.

