emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
fractional reserve banking</a> is deeply rooted in human nature. People hav=
e money, they would like to keep it somewhere safe, they would like it to g=
row, they would like to be able to get it back at any time. Other people ne=
ed money, they are willing to pay to borrow it, but they want it for a long=
 time =E2=80=94=C2=A0they want to be able to use it to buy a house or build=
 a business; they don=E2=80=99t want their lender to be able to demand the =
money back at any time. The savers and the borrowers just want different th=
ings. Why <em>would=C2=A0</em>anyone want to lock their money up for a long=
 time? Why=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>anyone want to borrow money for an unce=
rtain time?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are an enterprising middleman, you can =
try to convince one side or the other to do something that doesn=E2=80=99t =
quite match their desires =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cinvest your money long-te=
rm, but if you need it back we can <em>probably=C2=A0</em>find a way to get=
 it to you,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cborrow short-term, but you can <em>probabl=
y=C2=A0</em>keep rolling your debt for a long time=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but i=
t is easier and more appealing to just promise everyone exactly what they w=
ant. People who want to park their money give it to you and you promise to =
give it back whenever they want; people who want to borrow money borrow it =
from you and you tell them they=C2=A0can keep it for a long time;=C2=A0<em>=
probably=C2=A0</em>this all works out, but the mismatch is now your problem=
, not theirs. Of course it is also their problem, since if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t work out you are probably bankrupt. But you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>tel=
l=C2=A0</em>them that it=E2=80=99s their problem. This is better marketing.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This most obviously describes the=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cmaturity transformation=E2=80=9D function of traditional banking, =E2=80=
=9Ca superposition of=C2=A0fraud and genius that interposes itself between =
investors and entrepreneurs,=E2=80=9D in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW50ZXJmbHVpZGl0eS5j=
b20vdjIvMjY2OS5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf6cd5e20" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Steve Rand=
y Waldman=E2=80=99s words</a>. But it also describes a whole range of shado=
w banking activities, some of which are more genius and others of which are=
 more fraud. We have talked about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTcvZ3JlZW5zaWxsLWRpZG4tdC1qdXN0LWZpbmFuY2UtYmx1ZX=
