<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense you know that crypto has made it=
 because Gary Gorton wrote a paper about runs on crypto shadow banks. Here =
is =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/314884=
43.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X=
2lkPTQ0NDc3MDM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed6d220a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Bank Runs During =
Crypto Winter</a>,=E2=80=9D by Gorton and Jeffery Zhang:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCrypto Winter=E2=80=9D refers to a sy=
stemic event that occurred in the cryptocurrency ecosystem=E2=80=94what we =
call =E2=80=9Ccrypto space=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94in 2022. Crypto space was wrack=
ed by plummeting crypto prices, the troubles of a large crypto hedge fund, =
and runs on many crypto lending platforms. Several large crypto firms went =
bankrupt, and households and firms lost billions of dollars. Crypto investo=
rs are still feeling the aftershocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We begin with two observations. First, despite=
 mass marketing campaigns to the contrary, crypto lending platforms recreat=
ed banking all over again. Crypto lending platforms were vulnerable to runs=
 because, like all banks, they borrowed short and lent long. This is the es=
sence of banking, so we label these lending platforms =E2=80=9Ccrypto banks=
.=E2=80=9D Second, crypto space was largely circular. Once crypto banks obt=
ained deposits and investments, these firms borrowed, lent, and traded most=
ly with themselves. As a result, Crypto Winter did not cause the kind of fi=
nancial turmoil that we witnessed in either 2008 or 2020, and it did not ca=
use an economic recession.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We then pivot to a warning for regulators. The=
 next generation of crypto firms are linking up with the financial sector, =
which means their failures will spill over into the real economy. To contai=
n the inevitable growth of systemic risk, regulators should use banking law=
s to address a banking problem.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCrypto space was largely circular=E2=
=80=9D: Whereas traditional banking borrows short to lend long to people wh=
o want to build houses or start businesses, crypto shadow banking borrows c=
rypto short to lend crypto long to people who want to speculate on cryptocu=
rrencies. In some sense you=E2=80=99d expect this to create less of a matur=
ity mismatch =E2=80=94=C2=A0how long does anyone really need to borrow for =
to day-trade cryptocurrencies? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but on the other hand the col=
lateral is much riskier. If you borrow to buy a house and default, the bank=
 gets the house. If you borrow to buy some magic beans and default, the ban=
k gets some beans.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One point that Gorton and Zhang make is that, =
in the US, efforts at crypto regulation are largely about either securities=
 law or commodities regulation, but the actual problem of 2022 was=C2=A0<em=
>banking</em>.=C2=A0Securities regulation is about giving investors=C2=A0fu=
ll information so they can make informed decisions about what companies to =
invest in. Bank regulation is the <em>opposite</em>; it assumes that bank d=
epositors should=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>have to care much about what their =
banks are up to; bankers and=C2=A0regulators and supervisors worry about a =
bank=E2=80=99s asset quality and liquidity and capital ratios so that <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDUvYmFuay1zdG=
9ja3MtbG9vay13b3JzZS10aGFuLWJhbmtzLWRvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJ=
nV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNSZ1=
dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9f3152a4" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  depositors can be information-insensitive</a>. To the extent crypto is re=
-creating=C2=A0<em>banking</em>, regulators should respond by re-creating=
=C2=A0<em>bank regulation</em>. And a cornerstone of modern bank regulation=
 is deposit insurance. Gorton and Zhang write:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In all likelihood, applying bankin=
g law to crypto banks would require an act of Congress. Doing so would subj=
ect crypto banks to rigorous regulation but would also provide crypto banks=
 with deposit insurance paired with <em>enhanced supervision</em>.</p></blo=
ckquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean! That is one approach. My impression is=
 that most people running crypto exchanges=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>would =
not like US banking regulators to tell them where to invest their money (=
=E2=80=9Cnot crypto=E2=80=9D?), and also that most US regulators=C2=A0<em>r=
eally=C2=A0</em>would not like to guarantee the liabilities of crypto excha=
nges? US regulators are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjMvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLWNvaW5iYXNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1=
MTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV=
0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB37726584" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  not all that sure that crypto exchanges are <em>legal=
</em></a>. If your concern is that crypto shadow banks are becoming more in=
terconnected with the real economy, and that therefore future runs on those=
 shadow banks might be more destructive, there are two ways to go:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Protect crypto shadow banks from runs=
, with deposit insurance and regulation; or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">Protect the real economy from crypto shadow banks, by making it r=
eally hard for the traditional financial system to connect with crypto firm=
s.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators seem to be choosing Option 2, wh=
ich =E2=80=A6 seems =E2=80=A6=C2=A0right =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to me? As a matter =
of regulatory preferences but also as a matter of <em>crypto=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0</em>preferences. Just imagine implementing Option 1. Imagine the meetin=
g between the US Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and, like, Tether, to talk=
 about supervision and deposit insurance.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile here is a Chicago Fed Letter by Radh=
ika Patel and Jonathan Rose titled=C2=A0=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2hpY2Fnb2Zl=
ZC5vcmcvcHVibGljYXRpb25zL2NoaWNhZ28tZmVkLWxldHRlci8yMDIzLzQ3OQ/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB2e1400f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">A Retrospective on the Crypto Runs of 2022</=
a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In this article, we describe the s=
pectacular collapse of several crypto-asset platforms in 2022 following inv=
estment losses and widespread customer withdrawals. These platforms offered=
 and marketed to customers a number of products and services related to cry=
pto-assets, including high-yield investments, trading, and custody services=
. The platforms were subject to run risk: They allowed customers to withdra=
w funds on demand while using those funds to make illiquid and risky invest=
ments, in part to generate the high rates of returns promised to customers =
on investment products. In one of the most severe episodes, customers withd=
rew a quarter of their investments from the platform FTX in just one day, a=
ccording to our analysis of data from its bankruptcy filing. These episodes=
 together formed a classic financial crisis in a novel setting that has rai=
sed urgent policy concerns.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One finding here is that the crypto shadow ban=
ks had very=C2=A0<em>fast=C2=A0</em>runs; crypto shadow banking sort of nec=
essarily takes place online, =E2=80=9Cwith customers withdrawing funds thro=
ugh apps or web portals with ease.=E2=80=9D When there were runs on US regi=
onal banks this spring, it seems that bankers and regulators were surprised=
 by the speed of the bank runs in an era of largely app- and web-based bank=
ing. I suppose the crypto bank runs foreshadowed that a bit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another finding is that, =E2=80=9Cwhile the pl=
atforms had many retail clients, the runs were spearheaded by customers wit=
h large holdings, some of which were sophisticated institutional customers.=
=E2=80=9D This is related to the circularity of crypto that Gorton and Zhan=
g write about: Crypto shadow banks were borrowing from and lending to each =
other, crypto hedge funds were borrowing from one platform to lend on anoth=
er platform, and so they were particularly attuned to the risks of those pl=
atforms. In a sense crypto shadow banks were trying to provide information-=
insensitive deposits, but in another sense nothing in crypto is really info=
rmation-insensitive: Everyone=E2=80=99s account on every crypto platform is=
 a gambling account; nobody has their money at Celsius just because that=E2=
=80=99s where their employer direct deposited their paycheck and that=E2=80=
=99s where their automatic bill-pay is set up.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Crypto depositors are just naturally going to be more risk-aware =
than bank depositors, which makes crypto shadow banks more run-prone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another finding is that the crypto shadow bank=
s were pretty bad banks:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Efforts to generate high returns c=
aused these platforms to hold insufficient liquidity buffers. At FTX, Bankm=
an-Fried stated that FTX had held enough liquidity to meet 24 times average=
 daily withdrawals, which he stated turned out to be 80% of what was withdr=
awn in one day at the height of the run. Celsius used an internal stress sc=
enario that assumed a 20% outflow of customer funds in response to 40%=E2=
=80=9350% price drops, which would appear to be a conservative scenario; ho=
wever, in 2022, when Celsius=E2=80=99s liquidity buffer became insufficient=
 according to that stress scenario, the company adopted a weaker scenario i=
nvolving smaller price drops. BlockFi=E2=80=99s liquidity strategy aimed to=
 hold 10% of customer funds in assets that can be immediately liquidated an=
d 50% in assets that could be liquidated within seven calendar days. All of=
 these liquidity buffers were evidently insufficient, and it is hard to ver=
ify whether they ever existed.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What conclusion do you draw about bank regulat=
ion here? Like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto shadow banks had inadequate li=
quidity buffers, so they should have been regulated, because US banking reg=
ulators would have made them have higher liquidity buffers; or</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto shadow banks had inadequate=C2=A0liquid=
ity buffers, because their business of lending against volatile collateral =
was incredibly risky and run-prone, and if US banking regulators had superv=
ised these platforms they probably=C2=A0<em>still=C2=A0</em>would have had =
runs and gone bust (like several actual banks did recently!), but it would =
be the government=E2=80=99s fault?</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile at Bloomberg, <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTUvc29tZS1wb3B1bGFyLWNyeXB0by1jb21=
wYW5pZXMtbGFjay1ib2FyZHMtYXVkaXRzLWRlc3BpdGUtZnR4LXMtZmFsbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNT=
E1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1d=
G1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bca7f22fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Emily Nicolle reports</a> that many big crypto companie=
s do not have audited financial statements or independent =E2=80=94=C2=A0or=
, often, any =E2=80=94=C2=A0boards of directors:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg News surveyed 60 major crypto compan=
ies in the first quarter =E2=80=94 spanning the breadth of exchanges, minin=
g companies, analytics businesses and token issuers =E2=80=94 to gauge the =
state of governance and controls in the sector. 1 Many of these companies, =
which include the likes of Binance, Coinbase Global Inc., Tether and OpenSe=
a, oversee the flow of tens of billions of dollars in assets daily. And whi=
le a fair number do adhere to traditional standards, many operate outside t=
he norm. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Around half of the businesses surveyed current=
ly engage an independent auditor to assess their finances, the findings sho=
wed. Meanwhile, 63% of the companies had an independent board of directors =
=E2=80=93 meaning that they had at least one non-executive member. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0Among those without independent boards were Tether, Huobi and Magi=
c Eden, whose boards were either only advisory or entirely staffed by compa=
ny executives.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also=C2=A0at Bloomberg, here is Christopher Be=
am with =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
1488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIzLWNyeXB0=
by13aW50ZXIvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXR=
tX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdH=
VmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0648a03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Tales From the Crypto Winte=
r</a>.=E2=80=9D Beam=E2=80=99s friend George is still a believer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">George, despite the frauds, the constant hacks=
 and the market=E2=80=99s collapse, says he still has faith. =E2=80=9CI sti=
ll believe blockchain is a revolutionary development,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=
=80=9CIn 10, 20, 50 years, I do believe=E2=80=94I want to believe, badly=E2=
=80=94that we=E2=80=99ll look back and say Bitcoin was an invention on the =
scale of the printing press or the internet.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In their seminal 1956 social psychology study,=
 When Prophecy Fails, Leon Festinger, Henry Riecken and Stanley Schachter d=
escribed how followers of a doomsday cult responded when their prophet=E2=
=80=99s precise predictions of apocalypse turned out to be false: They just=
 pushed the date back. Some became even stronger believers and proselytized=
 more. They=E2=80=99d already committed too much, perhaps quitting their jo=
bs or giving away money, to accept that there was nothing to it. The study =
became a classic example of the =E2=80=9Ccognitive dissonance=E2=80=9D that=
 occurs when evidence contradicts one=E2=80=99s model of the world.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh and here is =E2=80=9CBitcoin Bulls Trip on =
a Frog as <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443=
.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTQ=
vYml0Y29pbi1idGMtYnVsbHMtbnVyc2UtbG9zc2VzLWFzLXBlcGUtbWVtZWNvaW4tZnJlbnp5LW=
ZhZGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5630e78" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Pepe Memecoin Frenzy</a> Signals=
 Market Top=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A frog-themed digital token that=E2=80=99s onl=
y been around for a month may be signaling pain ahead for Bitcoin bulls.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading in memecoins =E2=80=94 crypto assets t=
hat can be inspired by viral images and memes and attract loyal social-medi=
a communities but otherwise lack in inherent utility =E2=80=94 soared in re=
cent days. Leading the pack was Pepe, a newfangled amphibian-themed token, =
which sparked frenzied speculation and spawned many copycats ever since its=
 birth in April.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pepe was obsessively promoted on Twitter befor=
e and after its launch, and it peaked at a market value of more than $1.6 b=
illion on May 5 before reversing course and plummeting as much as 70% in fo=
llowing days, according to CoinMarketCap. The ill-fated frog =E2=80=94 whic=
h, like many memecoins, never traded higher than a fraction of a cent even =
at its height =E2=80=94 took Bitcoin and Ether down with it. Both coins hav=
e dropped about 10% since May 5, a notable step-down after four straight mo=
nths of gains.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yep yep yep the printing press, absolutely.</p=
>
