<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There were no credit default swaps on Credit S=
uisse Group AG=E2=80=99s additional tier 1 capital securities, I think for =
good reason. The purpose of the AT1s =E2=80=94=C2=A0we <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc=
3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVk=
aXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTUmdXRtX2NhbXB=
haWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB08a9de93" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked ab=
out them in March</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0was to be written down to zero if Cred=
it Suisse got in trouble; Credit Suisse did get in trouble, and the AT1s we=
re accordingly written down to zero. The AT1s were meant to, and did, shift=
 some of the risk of the bank=E2=80=99s failure from Swiss taxpayers to inv=
estors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The purposes of CDS are mostly (1) to help len=
ders and investors hedge their credit risk and (2) to allow speculators to =
bet=C2=A0<em>against=C2=A0</em>the credit of a company. The AT1s were suppo=
sed to be sold to people =E2=80=94=C2=A0large sophisticated asset managers,=
 foreign high-net-worth investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0who voluntarily took on th=
e risk of a Credit Suisse collapse, to put some of the tail risk of the ban=
king system in the hands of people who could bear it. If they all hedged by=
 buying CDS from a bank, that would defeat the purpose; you don=E2=80=99t w=
ant some other bank secretly holding all that risk. Meanwhile, you don=E2=
=80=99t necessarily want to encourage a market for people to speculate that=
 a big global bank will fail and be taken over by the government; AT1 CDS f=
or speculative purposes seems kind of dangerous.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there was CDS on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99=
s senior bonds, and on its subordinated bonds, but not on its AT1 capital s=
ecurities. And when Credit Suisse was seized by the Swiss government and so=
ld to UBS Group AG, its AT1s were written down to zero but its senior bonds=
 and subordinated bonds were untouched, so its CDS was not triggered. Excep=
t that now some hedge funds are asking, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTIvY2RzLWNvbW1pdHRlZS1hZ3JlZXMtdG8tY29uc2lkZXIt=
Y3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1wYXlvdXQtcXVlc3Rpb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTE1Jn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea5494cd" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  what if it was</a>?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Credit Derivatives Determinations Committe=
e agreed to consider whether a =E2=80=9Cgovernmental intervention credit ev=
ent=E2=80=9D occurred when Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s Additional Tier=
 1 bonds were written down, opening the door for a potential payout on the =
swaps.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The acceptance by a panel of about a dozen ban=
ks and asset managers is the first step in a process that will determine if=
 credit default swaps tied to the Swiss bank will be triggered. Funds inclu=
ding FourSixThree Capital and Diameter Capital Partners have been buying sw=
aps insuring Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s subordinated bonds, betting that the c=
ontroversial writedown could prompt a payout of the derivative contracts, B=
loomberg previously reported.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2RzZGV0ZXJtaW5hdGlv=
bnNjb21taXR0ZWVzLm9yZy9jZHMvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1ncm91cC1hZy8/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB08f0a924" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> determinations committee page</a> on the que=
stion. The funds=E2=80=99 arguments=C2=A0are not public, but <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
ZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZGFjZDM5YTItN2Y3MC00NGUzLTkxZDEtN2UzMDBmOTAxZGFk/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBf23e9b81" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here is Sujeet Indap at FT Alphaville=
</a> trying to figure them out. The gist of it<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0is that CDS on Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s subordinated bonds is trig=
gered not only if=C2=A0<em>those=C2=A0</em>bonds are written down (they wer=
e not), but also if any bonds that were =E2=80=9Cnot subordinated=E2=80=9D =
to them were written down. And while the AT1s are in some obvious practical=
 sense subordinated to Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s other bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
hey were written down, while the other bonds are fine! =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is=
 not so clear that that=E2=80=99s the case from the actual language of the =
offering documents. (=E2=80=9CIf Circumstance X occurs, Bond Y will pay bac=
k zero but Bond Z will be repaid in full=E2=80=9D does=C2=A0<em>not</em>, s=
trictly speaking, mean that Bond Y is =E2=80=9Csubordinated=E2=80=9D to Bon=
d Z.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile all of this only makes sense because=
 interest rates have gone up. Indap:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Given that the subordinated bond Credit Suisse=
 issued in 2000 has already been repaid and its other bonds that are eligib=
le for a CDS auction were not impaired in the UBS merger, you might assume =
there is little reward in store for those betting on a surprise CDS default=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is where the hedge funds betting on a pay=
out are banking on the sharp moves higher in interest rates over the past y=
ear coming to their aid, however.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group has a bond outstanding tha=
t is trading at around 65 cents on the dollar, purely as a function of the =
dramatic change in underlying rates since it was issued at the end of 2021 =
(the bond in question has a skimpy 0.625 per cent coupon and a decade-long =
2033 maturity, making it particularly sensitive to interest rate changes).<=
/p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way CDS works is, roughly, that if it is t=
riggered then it pays out 100 cents on the dollar=C2=A0<em>minus=C2=A0</em>=
the current value of the underlying bonds. Usually that value is low (and C=
DS pays a lot), if the issuer has really gone bankrupt, or roughly 100 cent=
s on the dollar (and CDS pays very little),=C2=A0if the issuer is fine but =
the CDS has been triggered for some weird technical reasons. Here the CDS h=
as been triggered for some weird technical reason =E2=80=94=C2=A0these bond=
s are fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there is still potential for a real payout be=
cause they have lost value due to interest rates.=C2=A0We <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31488443.258437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDEvanBtb3JnYW4tZ290LWEtZG=
VhbC1vbi1maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTUmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0a21054c" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked a c=
ouple of weeks ago</a> about people trading CDS on the US government. There=
, too, the bet is that a US debt default would=C2=A0<em>trigger=C2=A0</em>C=
DS, but that US bonds would be relatively unimpaired (because=C2=A0<em>prob=
ably </em>a debt-ceiling default would be cured quickly). But because inter=
est rates have moved so much so quickly, long-term US government bonds =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0as well as Credit Suisse subordinated bonds =E2=80=94 trade wel=
l below 100 cents on the dollar, so triggering CDS is valuable.=C2=A0</p>
